problem link : https://leetcode.com/problems/merge-intervals/description/

Intuition
for this problem we need to understand wemare given intervals if any interval overlaps then we want to merge them , now how will we know that an interval is overlapping ?

suppose [[1,5],[3,7]]
start1 = 1, end1 = 5 , start2 = 3 , end2 = 7

now we can clearly see that they need to get merged but mathematical logic is when end 1 >= start2 then only we will need merging

but suppose [[1,5],[7,10]]
start1 = 1, end1 = 5 , start2 = 7 , end2 = 10
when end1 < start2 then there will be no need of merging and there will be independent inetrvals

Approach
sort the intervals from start as sorting by start allows us to merge overlapping intervals in one go ,

initalize result array where we are going to stre merged intervals

start1 , end1 is the first inerval we are going to use for comparison

iterate the array from second interval
start2 and end2 will be the second interval used for comparison

if end1>= start2: merge the interval and update start1 and end1 and keep it for further comparison and update start2 and end 2 into next i

if end 1 < start2 : no need to merge we have found an independent interval store start1 and end1 in result and update start1 and end1 to start2 and end2

during each iteration either we merge intervals by updating start1 and end1 and merging intervals into them

or we find an independent interval and we store inital start1 and end1 into result and update current start1 and end1 to start2 and end2

after iterating the array , one last indepent start1 and end1 remains so we store them in result and return result

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(nlogn)

Space complexity:
O(n)

Code
class Solution:
    def merge(self, intervals: List[List[int]]) -> List[List[int]]:
        intervals.sort()
        result = []
        start1 = intervals[0][0]
        end1 = intervals[0][1]
        for i in range(1,len(intervals)):
            start2 = intervals[i][0]
            end2 = intervals[i][1]
            if end1 >= start2:
                start1 = start1
                end1 = max(end1,end2)
            else:
                result.append([start1,end1])
                start1 = start2 
                end1 = end2
        result.append([start1,end1])
        return result
